So the issue is that even though the port expects to be linking via GNU ld (checking if the linker (/usr/local/bin/ld) is GNU ld... yes) it actually links using /usr/bin/c++:

[ 75%] Linking CXX executable jt9
/usr/local/bin/cmake -E cmake_link_script CMakeFiles/jt9.dir/link.txt --verbose=1
/usr/bin/c++ -O2 -pipe -fstack-protector-strong -isystem /usr/local/include -fno-strict-aliasing  -isystem /usr/local/include -Wall -Wextra -fexceptions -frtti -Wno-pragmas -fopenmp --std=gnu++11 -pthread -O2 -pipe -fstack-protector-strong -isystem /usr/local/include -fno-strict-aliasing  -isystem /usr/local/include  -DNDEBUG -fdata-sections -ffunction-sections  -Wl,-rpath=/usr/local/lib/gcc13  -L/usr/local/lib/gcc13 -Wl,--undefined-version -L/usr/local/lib -fstack-protector-strong  -Wl,--gc-sections -fopenmp -Xlinker --dependency-file=CMakeFiles/jt9.dir/link.d CMakeFiles/jt9.dir/jt9_autogen/mocs_compilation.cpp.o CMakeFiles/jt9.dir/lib/jt9.f90.o CMakeFiles/jt9.dir/lib/jt9a.f90.o -o jt9   -L/usr/local/lib/gcc13/gcc/x86_64-portbld-freebsd15.0/13.3.0  -L/usr/local/x86_64-portbld-freebsd15.0/lib  -Wl,-rpath,/usr/local/lib/qt5: libwsjt_fort_omp.a libwsjt_cxx.a libfort_qt.a /usr/local/lib/libfftw3f_threads.so /usr/local/lib/libfftw3f.so /usr/local/lib/libboost_log_setup.so /usr/local/lib/qt5/libQt5Core.so.5.15.16 -lgfortran -lssp_nonshared -lquadmath

and lld (/usr/bin/ld) just ignores the .note.GNU-stack:

    // The GNU linker uses .note.GNU-stack section as a marker indicating
    // that the code in the object file does not expect that the stack is
    // executable (in terms of NX bit). If all input files have the marker,
    // the GNU linker adds a PT_GNU_STACK segment to tells the loader to
    // make the stack non-executable. Most object files have this section as
    // of 2017.
    //
    // But making the stack non-executable is a norm today for security
    // reasons. Failure to do so may result in a serious security issue.
    // Therefore, we make LLD always add PT_GNU_STACK unless it is
    // explicitly told to do otherwise (by -z execstack). Because the stack
    // executable-ness is controlled solely by command line options,
    // .note.GNU-stack sections are simply ignored.
    if (name == ".note.GNU-stack")
      return &InputSection::discarded;

The easiest way of addressing this toolchain issue will be to pass -Wl,-z,execstack to the linking stage. If shurd's patch indeed covers all of the cases that's much better than fixing the toolchain issue (but we should make nxstack explicit rather than relying on a toolchain bug).
